· ea It istobe noticed that many peculiarities in deciension and conjugation are found only at the close of a verse or its equivalent, and are therefore due to metrical reasons. Thus, in the case of perfect tenses which are commonly contracted, the full forms are used regularly only at the close of a line; cf. resolverint (494), hut decrerat (238). See note on 10. The same principle is observed in the case of aiem, etc, as compared with eim, etc.; the present subjunctive forms in -r'm,· the infinitive form in -r'er,· the imperative focc; infieri (792) as compared with frere, periculum beside periclum (131); and dextera (734, 751) beside dectm (289).
